[2
Date: 12 Apr 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Telegraph, 13 Apr 2001 [edited
<http://www.telegraph.co.uk:80/et?ac=002559874442765&rtmo=Lx3KLLyd&atmo=tttt
tttd&pg=/et/01/4/13/nfnm113.html>

Scientists explain today for the first time the reason slaughter around the
areas affected by FMD is more effective than ring vaccination. They say
ring culling or vaccination is essential if the scale of the epidemic is to
be reduced from a worst-case scenario, where half the country's livestock
would eventually have to be slaughtered. But "culling is more effective
than vaccination," says Dr Neil Ferguson, of Imperial College, in Science
with colleagues Dr Christl Donnelly and Prof Roy Anderson. Prof Anderson's
team concludes "extensive culling is sadly the only option for controlling
the epidemic."
Dr Ferguson's calculations show rapid culling on infected farms within 24
hours, and of surrounding farms within 48 hours, is required to stem the
epidemic. The cull on surrounding farms removes the "fuel" for the
epidemic, but ring vaccination is equally effective but must be more
widespread to have the same effect.
Vaccines, which consist of inactivated FMD virus, take up to 4 days to
produce immunity and vaccinated animals may harbor and pass on the virus.
The report says "culling reduces the susceptible population and reduces
transmission by removing infected (but undiagnosed) animals, while
vaccination essentially only achieves the former." Because vaccinated
animals need to be culled anyway to meet conditions allowing export
restrictions to be lifted, this "further questions the benefit of such
vaccination policies".
The team shows that movement restrictions introduced soon after the first
confirmed case resulted in a drop in the spread of the disease over a
distance of 9000 meters from 38 percent to 12 percent. However, these
measures were not enough, because the computer model revealed each case
would trigger up to 4 new cases. The 21 Mar 2001 measures - dubbed the
24/48 policy - cut that to closer to one new case, bringing the outbreak
under control by the end of March.
The report concludes that logistical difficulties in processing large
numbers of animals and significant delays between reporting cases and
culling on farms are still hindering efforts to fight the disease.
